ABSTRACT

A transcriptome is the whole set of mRNA molecules in a determined cell and condition. This study uses RNA-seq data taken from thyroid tissues with different degrees of lymphoid infiltrations (Not infiltrated, Small focal infiltrates and Extensive lymphoyd infiltrates) with the objective to find differentially expressed genes (DEGs) between the different conditions.

Here, we also analyse the biological processes (GO terms) related to this DEGs and demonstrate that the more activated pathways in the more infiltrated tissues compared to the less infiltrated ones are those pathways and funcitons related to the immune system.

OBJECTIVES

The objectives of these study are:

  • To analyze the effects that lymphoid infiltration in the thyroid produce to its transcriptome and to find the differentially expressed genes in the infiltrated tissues in comparison to less (or not) infiltrated tissues.
  • To see the biological processes that are activated and inhibited upon lymphoid infiltration.

In terms of learning, the objectives are:

  • To understand the statistical methods and the biology behind the RNA-sequencing analyses.
  • To practice the methods learned during the lessons.
  • To acquire new knowledge in other methods by searching information in diverse RNAseq-related documentation.

If we had the original reference of the data retrieved from the Genotype-Tissue Expression repository (GTEx) [^1^](#1), we could have more information about the objective of the original study and, hence, compare our analysis to the original one.

METHODS AND MATERIAL

Study

This study contains RNA-seq data retrieved from the Genotype-Tissue Expression repository (GTEx) [^1^](#1). This data has 292 samples from a thyroid study that are divided in three groups:

  • Not infiltrated tissues (NIT): 236 samples
  • Small focal infiltrates (SFI): 42 samples
  • Extensive lymphoid infiltrates (ELI): 14 samples

Workflow

The general workflow of the process can be consulted in Figure 1.

Figure 1._Workflow of the analysis_. Black text within boxes represents the steps of the analysis, blue text represents the functions used in each step of the analyses and black text outside of boxes represents the inputs and outputs of each function.

The code used in all the analyses can be consulted in the code section of the appendix, as well as a more extensive explanation of each step followed in the analyses. In the results section, only some explanations are done in order to follow the analyses in a easier way.

Steps

The steps of the analysis can be divided in:

RAW DATA

  1. Downloading and reading: downloading the targets.csv and counts.csv files and, using read.csv(), read them and store them in the R environment. Then, format the ENSEMBLE GENE IDS from the counts file to remove the version (i.e. ENSG00000000000.1)

  2. Subsetting data: using the R fucntions filter() and sample_n() from dplyr, subset the targets file to get 10 samples of each group (targets_sub). After that, using the subset of targets and the function select() from dplyr, subset the counts in order to get the gene counts in the subseted samples of each group (final counts table: counts_sub).

DE ANALYSIS

  1. DESeq dataset: create a table named colData to store the sample names of counts_sub (in the rownames) and the group where each sample corresponds. Then, using the counts_sub and colData create the DESeq dataset with DESeqDataSetFromMatrix() from the R package DESeq2. The output of this step is a DESeq dataset.

  2. DESeq: using the funtion DESeq() from the R package DESeq2, we estimate the size factors and the dispersions of the data, and then we fit data to a model. The output of this step is a dds object. Moreover, using the function counts() extract the normalized counts of all samples.

  3. Contrasts: for each contrast, relevel de conditions in the dds object in order to get the correct order for the contrast. Then using the results() and nbinomWaldTest() functions from DESeq2() package, compute the log2FoldChange values and p-values for each gene in each contrast. The output of this step is a DESeq results object.

  4. Log2FC shrinkage: using the lfcShrink() function, perform the log2FC shrinkage on the output of step 5. The output of this step is a DESeq results object.

  5. DEG annotation: using the custom function DEannot(), annotate the genes in the output of step 6 as upregulated, downregulated or not differentially expressed. To be called as differentially expressed, a gene must have an adjusted p-value <= 0.5 and an absolute value of log2FC > 1.5 (increment or reduction of gene expression by 2.25 times). The output of this step is a data frame with the log2FC, p-values, EnsemblIDs, etc.

PCA

  1. PCA: Using the dds object that outputs from the step 4, do a rlog transformation using the rlog() function from DESeq2. Then, with a custom function named pcaplot2(), that is a modification of the plotPCA() from pcaExplorer, do and plot the Principal Component Analysis (PCA).

DE Visualization

  1. Heatmap of normalized counts: take the 1000 genes with a greater (absolute) log2FC in the contrast ELI vs NIT and use this list to filter the genes in the normalized counts matrix. Then, using the Heatmap() function from ComplexHeatmap, compute the heatmap of the normalized counts for all in this subsetted list of genes.

  2. Heatmap of log2FC: using the same gene list as in step 9, filter the genes in the contrasts that output from step 7. Then take the log2FC values of each contrast and, using the Heatmap() function from ComplexHeatmap, build a heatmap with the log2FC values of each contrasts in the subsetted list of genes.

  3. MA plots: using the function plotMA() and the output of the step 6, draw MA plots for each contrast. The MA plots use the mean of the normalized counts for each gene (X axis) and draws it against its log2FC value in a determined contrast.

  4. Volcano plots: using the customfunction VolcanoPlot2() and the dataframe that outputs from DEanot(), draw the volcanoplots for each contrast. A volcano plot is a scatterplot that draws the log2FC values X axis against the -log10(adjusted pvalue) in the Y axis. Usually, the points are colored depending on the DE state (upregulated, downregulated or not differentially expressed).

  5. Overlaps of DEGs: using the custom functions subsetDegs() and overlapDE(), we can

GO enrichment of DEGs

  1. GO enrichment: using the functions compareCluster() and enrichGO() from clusterProfiler we retrieve the enriched GO terms in the up and downregulated genes in each of our contrasts. Then, with the function dotplot() from enrichplot, draw a dotplot with the enriched GO terms for each of the gene lists.

RESULTS & DISCUSSION

Raw data

After reading the target.csv and counts.csv files, the first thing to take into account is the formatting of the gene ID, since its format is ENSEMBL ID and contains the version of the gene annotation at the end of the ID, but it can cause problems in further steps that require to change the gene ID format. Alternatively, we could change the format to SYMBOL in order to have more understandable gene IDs, but in the process some genes are usually lost, so this alternative step wonât be performed.

Then, since we are required to work with only 10 samples from each group, we have to be aware that, specially in the case of the NIT condition which has a lot of replicates, the results can vary a lot depending on which replicates we use. To minimize the variation in this case, we must use a seed before subsetting the replicates.

Differential expression analysis

The differentiall expression (DE) analysis aims to find which genes are activated or inhibited when comparing two conditions. In our case, after infiltration of limphocytes to the thyroid (since we always compare the condition with more infiltration against the condition with less infilitration),

Data processing

Before creating the dataset that will be used for the DE analysis with DESeq2, we could remove some low expressed genes based on their counts in order to use less memory and increase the computation speed. The filtering is also statistically useful, since the amount of statistical tests that have to be performed is smaller and the adjustment of the p-value is easier, increasing the power of the tests.

Nevertheless, the gene filtering is not performed in our pipline, since DESeq2 has a more stringent filtering step that already increases the statistical power.

We also have to do the contrasts between the different groups/conditions. The contrasts that will be performed are:

  • Contrast 1: ELI vs NIT
  • Contrast 2: ELI vs SFI
  • Contrast 3: SFI vs NIT

After defining the contrasts, thresholds for the adjusted-pvalue and log2FC have to be decided in order to call a gene as differentially expressed gene (DEG). To be called as DEG, a gene has must have an adjusted p-value <= 0.05 and an absolute value for the log2FC > 1.5. The p-value adjustment of DESeq follows a Benjamini-Hochberg procedure and it is prefered to use the adjusted p-value instead of the p-value because when multiple testing is performed (like in DE analyses), just by change, some of the tests will result significative when its significance is not correct.

PCA

The Principal Component Analysis (PCA) is a good way to measure the variation between several samples. Normally, it takes the normalized counts of a subset of highly variable genes (i.e.Â 500 most variable genes) and calculate the variance of these genes using all the samples.

Usually, in a PCA, the replicates from the same condition should cluster together, whereas different conditions can cluster close or far depending on their similarities.

Figure 2. Princiapal component analysis of the 30 samples subtracted (10 replicates for each condition) from the original counts.csv file.

As seen in the Figure 2, the samples (even replicates of the same condition) are distributed along all the plot, meaning that there is a lot of variance between them. In the case of the NIT and SFI replicates, they cluster extremely close to each other in some cases, which suggest that the gene expression in these conditions is very similar. On the other hand, the replicates from ELI, despite some of them clustering far from each other, they donât cluster very close to the other conditions (compared to NIT and SFI), indicating that ELI condition might be the most different compared to three conditions.

Visualization

To visualize the gene expression, there are several methods:

Heatmaps

Heatmaps are a way to visualize different samples or conditions and compare them. They can be used to look at a group of genes and compare different values (i.e.Â normalized counts, log2FC) between different samples or conditions.

In our case, using all the genes would not be very clever, since most of the genes in a genome are not differentially expressed and wouldnât make a difference between the samples. Instead, we will take the contrast of ELI vs NIT, which is expected to be the one with most DEGs, and will subset the 100 most differentially expressed genes (highest absolute value of log2FC). This list of 100 genes is the one that will be used to compare the different samples.

Alternatively, different gene signatures can be searched in order to have a list of genes that are typical from a determined cell state (i.e.Â stemness, leukemia, etc).

Normalized counts

The normalized counts can be useful either to compare different conditions or to compare intra-condition replicates.

A good thing we can do is to build a heatmap with the normalized counts of the most differentially expressed genes (1000 genes) in the contrast ELI vs NIT. This way, we can look visually at the differences between the different conditions and whether the intra-condition replicates are similar regarding the expression of these genes.

Figure 3. Heatmap with the normalized counts of the 100 most DE genes (ELI vs NIT) with all samples clustered by replicates

In Figure 3, which reperesents the DESeq2-normalized counts for a subset of 100 genes that are higly DE in the contrast ELI vs NIT, it can be observed that most genes in the replicates of NIT and SFI are in blue, meaning that they have a low gene expression (low normalized counts), whereas the ELI replicates have a lot of highly expressed genes. Furthermore, either visually or using a clustering method, it can be observed that SFI and NIT are similar between them, but very different compared to ELI. This is consistent with what has been observed in the PCA of the Figure 2.

Log2FCs

Heatmaps of Log2FC are useful to compare the different contrasts.

#filtering contrasts
contrast1_filt <- contrast1.res_annot[which(contrast1.res_annot$Geneid %in% genes$Geneid),] %>% dplyr::select(log2FoldChange)

Figure 4. Heatmap with the log2FC of the 100 most DE genes (ELI vs NIT) comparing the three studied contrasts.

In Figure 4, consistently with what has been observed previously, it can be clearly observed that the contrast SFI vs NIT does not have many DE genes. Instead, the other two contrasts (ELI vs SFI, ELI vs NIT) show a large amount of genes with high log2FC, specially in the contrast ELI vs NIT.

This suggests that upon lymphoid inflitration to the thyrioid, a lot of genes are activated and, since we are talking about lymphoid infiltration, those genes may be putatively related to the immune system.

MA plots

MA plots are plots that draw the mean of the normalized counts (between all the replicates in the study) in the X axis and the log2FC of the genes in a determined contrast in the Y axis. This way, a relation between the mean expression and the change in expression from a condition to another can be computed.

Figure 5. MA plots of the three studied contrasts.

Figure 5. MA plots of the three studied contrasts.

Figure 5. MA plots of the three studied contrasts.

Volcano plots

Volcano plots are probably the most useful way to visualize a DE analysis. They draw scatter plot with a point for each gene with the log2FC in the X axis and the -log10 of the adjusted p-value in the Y axis. Usually, they take a volcano-like shape because the genes with highest log2FC (in absolute value) are also those with more significance (and hence lower p-value). Moreover the color of the points can be set up depending on whether the gene is upregulated, downregulated or not differentially expressed.

Figure 6. Volcano plots of the different studied contrasts.

The volcano plots in Figure 6 confirm what has been seen with the MA plots: the conditions SFI and NIT (contrast 3) are very similar, since there are only a few genes called as differentially expressed. In the contrast 1 and 2, the number of differentially expressed genes (DEGs) is much higher.

Looking at the effects of the lymphoid infiltration (ELI > SFI > NIT), it increases the gene expression of a large amount of genes, either in the contrast ELI vs NIT or ELI vs SFI, whereas the number of downregulated genes is extremely low in comparison with the activated ones.

Overlaps

To see how many differentially expressed genes overlap between different contrasts, we can take the lists of gene names (ex. in ensembl id) and, using the custom function overlapDE() we will make the intersection of the DEG lists and plot the Venn diagrams. However, first of all we must separate the upregulated and downregulated genes and, to do it, we will use the custom function subsetDegs().

Figure 7. Venn diagrams of the intersections (between the three studied contrasts) of up and downregulated genes

Figure 7, shows two different things:

  • In the case of the upregulated genes, the contrasts 1 and 2 have a lot of overlapping genes (approximattely 50% for the contrast 1 and more than 90% for the contrast 2), indicating high similarity between them. The contrast 3 has more upregulated genes in common with the contrast 1 than contrast 2, which is interesting, since until now, we have observet higher similarity of contrast 3 with contrast 2 than with contrast 1.

  • When looking at the downregulated genes, the proportion of overlapping genes between contrasts 1 and 2 is much lower than in the case of the upregulated ones, being les than 33% of the genes in the contrast 1 and les than 15% for the genes in the contrast 2. In the case of the contrast 3, it has not any downregulated gene in common with the other two contrasts.

###GO enrichment

Gene ontology (GO) is a project that looks towars functional annoation of the genes (biological processes, molecular functions, cellular localizations). To look at the GO terms that are enriched in our DE genes is a good way to see what happens in the different samples and conditions.

Figure 8. Most enriched GO terms (for biological process) in our contrasts. GO terms have been called with a q-value cutoff of 0.15 amd a p-value cutoff of 0.1

As shown in Figure 8, when looking at the upregulated genes, the enriched GO terms are similar in contrasts ELI vs NIT and ELI vs SFI. As seen in the dotplot, these GO terms (biological process) are mainly related to processes of the immune system, such as lymphocyte and leukocyte proliferation or activation.

In the case of downregulated genes, the GO terms are less enriched, specially in the contrast ELI vs NIT, where we had to increase the q-value threshold to see some terms. We also see that downregulated genes of both contrasts have many differences in terms of gene ontologies: while in the ELI vs NIT the enriched GO terms are mainly related to cell fate and development (possibly due to a regression to a less differentiated state of the cells?, i.e.Â cancer, leukemia?), in the contrast of ELI vs SFI, the downregulated genes are more related to signal transduction processes.

In the contrast SFI vs NIT, the enriched GO terms for the upregulated genes are also related to processes of the immune system. However, some GO terms are also related to signal transduction, partially overlapping with those enriched in the downregulated genes of ELI vs SFI

CONCLUSION

In conclusion:

  • As there is more lymphoid infiltration (ELI > SFI > NIT) in the thyroid, more genes are differentially expressed.
  • The activated genes upon lymphoid inflitration to the thyroid are mainly related to the immune system, something that is expected because there are more immune system cells in a sample with high lymphoid inflitration (ie. ELI) than in a sample with low infiltration (i.e. NIT).
  • The downregulated genes upon inflitration can be related to signal transduction (Figure 8. ELI vs SFI - Down) or to cell fate and tissue/organ development (Figure 8. ELI vs NIT - Down). This last case could be caused because a putative less differentiated state of the cells in the sample.

Neverteless, we should gather more information and perform further studies to make a robust conclusion.

Code

Raw data

Read files

After downloading the files, we read them using the function read.csv(). Then, using str_sub() from the package stringr we modify the rownames from the counts file in orther to get the ENSEMBL ID without the version (i.e.Â ENSG00000000000.1 to ENSG00000000000).

#read files from counts
targets <- read.csv(file = "targets_counts/targets.csv", header = T, sep = ",")
counts  <- read.csv(file = "targets_counts/counts.csv", header = T, sep = ";", row.names = 1)

#format rownames of the counts file
ensemblID <- rownames(counts) %>% stringr::str_sub(start = 1, end = 15) 
ensemblID -> rownames(counts)

#get gene symbols
genesymbols <- bitr(ensemblID, fromType = "ENSEMBL", toType = "SYMBOL", OrgDb = org.Hs.eg.db)
#genesymbols$SYMBOL %>% length()

Filter samples

Once the gene ids have been formatted, we proceed to subset the targets in order to get 10 random samples from each group (NIT, SFI and ELI). Then, using this subset of targets (targets_sub), we can proceed to subset the counts in order to get all gene counts in the 30 samples present in targets_sub. Notice that the sample names in targets_sub do not have the same format as the ones in counts, so we will have to replace the â-â for â.â in targets_sub using the function gsub().

Alternatively, we can use bitr() function from clusterProfiler to change the gene names from ENSEMBL ID to SYMBOL in order to get more understandable gene names. Nevertheless, by doing that we lose more than half of the genes, so we will not change it and we will proceed with the ENSEMBL ID.

#set seed for the random subsetting
set.seed(972)

#subset targets by group (10 samples from each group)
targets_sub <- rbind(targets %>% filter(Group=="NIT") %>% sample_n(size = 10),
                     targets %>% filter(Group=="SFI") %>% sample_n(size = 10),
                     targets %>% filter(Group=="ELI") %>% sample_n(size = 10)) %>%
  
  mutate(Sample_Name = Sample_Name %>% gsub(pattern = "-", replacement = "."))

#subset counts by samples in targets_sub
counts_sub  <- counts[,targets_sub$Sample_Name]

#write files with targets sub and counts sub
write.table(x = targets_sub, file = "results/targets_sub.tsv", quote = F, sep = "\t", col.names = T)
write.table(x = counts_sub %>% mutate(GeneID = rownames(counts_sub)), file = "results/counts_sub.tsv", quote = F, sep = "\t", col.names = T)

Differential expression analysis

To do the differential expression (DE) analysis we can use several packages, such as limma-voom, edgeR or DESeq2, etc. In our case, the package used will be DESeq2 [^2^](#2).

DESeq2 takes the raw counts of each gene and calculates the dispersion of the gene expression using all the replicates in each condition. Then, it calculates the size factors in order to normalize the data and fits the data to a model. Finally, DESeq2 performs a Negative Binomial Wald Test to determine the fold-changes, their base-2 logarithms (log2FC), the p-values and the adjusted p-values of each gene in each of the comparisons made. Externally, we will use a package named apeglm to produce the srinkage of the log2FC.

Data processing

We already have the raw counts in counts_sub, however we need a table with the information of the samples (named colData), where we will write the sample names (Sample_Name in targets_sub) and their correspondent group (Group in targets_sub). After that, if the column names in counts_sub are equal to the row names of colData we will proceed to get the DESeq dataset using DESeqDataSetFromMatrix().

#create colData with samplenames and the group
colData <- targets_sub %>% dplyr::select(Sample_Name, Group) %>% tibble::column_to_rownames(var = "Sample_Name") %>% magrittr::set_colnames("condition")

# if colnames of counts_sub are equal to the rownames of colData, continue to get the DESeq dataset
if(colnames(counts_sub) == rownames(colData)){
  
  dds <- DESeq2::DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = counts_sub,
                                      colData = colData, 
                                      design = ~condition)
  
}

Once we have the DESeq dataset, we use DESeq() from DESeq2 to get the estimates of size factors and dispersions and then fits the data to a model.

Using other methods, one would filter the genes based on their counts (i.e.Â those genes with less than 10 counts in all samples would be filtered out). However, with DESeq2 we donât do that because DESeq2 already performs a more stringent filtering with the results() function in order to increase the power of the tests and to reduce the number of tests to perform.

#DESeq() function
# dds <- DESeq(dds)

#DESeq() function is equivalent to the following three funtions:
dds <- estimateSizeFactors(dds)
dds <- estimateDispersions(dds)
dds <- nbinomWaldTest(dds) #this one will be repeated for each contrast, so it is not absolutelly necessary here


#write normalized counts 
norm_counts <- counts(dds, normalized=T) %>% as.data.frame() %>% round(3) %>% tibble::rownames_to_column("GeneID")

#save dds object so we can continue from here next time
saveRDS(dds, file = "results/deseq.rds")

Now we have to do the contrasts between the different groups/conditions. The contrasts that will be performed are:

  • Contrast 1: ELI vs NIT
  • Contrast 2: ELI vs SFI
  • Contrast 3: SFI vs NIT

First we relevel the conditions in order to get the correct contrasts. Then, using nbinomWaldTest(), we perform the multiple testing to see how gene expressions change from one condition to another one. Using the function results(), results tables are generated, getting the log2FC and the corresponding (adjusted-) pvalue for each gene in each contrast. Finally, the results are passed through lfcShrink() in order to produce the log2FC shrinkage specifying the method âapeglmâ from the package apeglm.

# ---- CONTRAST 1 ---- #
contrast1 <- c("condition", "ELI", "NIT")
contrast1.dds <- dds

# relevel conditions
contrast1.dds$condition <- factor(contrast1.dds$condition, levels = c("NIT", "ELI", "SFI"))

# statistical testing
contrast1.dds <- nbinomWaldTest(contrast1.dds)

# getting results
contrast1.res <- results(contrast1.dds, contrast = contrast1)

#log2FC shrinkage
contrast1.res <- lfcShrink(dds = contrast1.dds, coef = "condition_ELI_vs_NIT", res = contrast1.res, type = "apeglm")


# ---- CONTRAST 2 ---- #
contrast2 <- c("condition", "ELI", "SFI")
contrast2.dds <- dds

# relevel conditions
contrast2.dds$condition <- factor(contrast2.dds$condition, levels = c("SFI", "ELI", "NIT"))

# statistical testing
contrast2.dds <- nbinomWaldTest(contrast2.dds)

# getting results
contrast2.res <- results(contrast2.dds, contrast = contrast2)

#log2FC shrinkage
contrast2.res <- lfcShrink(dds = contrast2.dds, coef = "condition_ELI_vs_SFI", res = contrast2.res, type = "apeglm")


# ---- CONTRAST 3 ---- #
contrast3 <- c("condition", "SFI", "NIT")
contrast3.dds <- dds

# relevel conditions
contrast3.dds$condition <- factor(contrast3.dds$condition, levels = c("NIT", "SFI", "ELI"))

# statistical testing
contrast3.dds <- nbinomWaldTest(contrast3.dds)

# getting results
contrast3.res <- results(contrast3.dds, contrast = contrast3)

#log2FC shrinkage
contrast3.res <- lfcShrink(dds = contrast3.dds, coef = "condition_SFI_vs_NIT", res = contrast3.res, type = "apeglm")
contrast1.res_annot <- contrast1.res[order(contrast3.res$padj),] %>% 
  data.frame() %>% tibble::rownames_to_column(var = "Geneid")

contrast2.res_annot <- contrast2.res[order(contrast2.res$padj),] %>%
  data.frame() %>% tibble::rownames_to_column(var = "Geneid")

contrast3.res_annot <- contrast3.res[order(contrast3.res$padj),] %>% 
  data.frame() %>% tibble::rownames_to_column(var = "Geneid")

Now, using the custom function DEannot() we will assing each gene as upregulated, downregulated or not differentially expressed (custom functions can be consluted in the GitHub repository). To be called as differentially expressed (either up or downregulated), a gene has to hava an adjusted p-value lower than 0.05 and an absolute value of log2FC greater than 1.5 (which means that the expression has been increased or decreased by 2.8284271 times). Alternatively, we can also use bitr() to change the EnsemblID to GeneSymbol in order to get more understandable gene names.

contrast1.res_annot <- DEannot(contrast1.res_annot)
contrast2.res_annot <- DEannot(contrast2.res_annot)
contrast3.res_annot <- DEannot(contrast3.res_annot)
dir.create(path = "results/deseq2", showWarnings = F, recursive = T)
write.table(contrast1.res_annot, file = "results/deseq2/eli_vs_nit-diff_exp.tsv", quote = F, sep = "\t", row.names = F)
write.table(contrast2.res_annot, file = "results/deseq2/eli_vs_sfi-diff_exp.tsv", quote = F, sep = "\t", row.names = F)
write.table(contrast3.res_annot, file = "results/deseq2/sfi_vs_nit-diff_exp.tsv", quote = F, sep = "\t", row.names = F)

PCA

In order to see how the replicates of each condition are related between them, we can do a principal component analysis (PCA).

First of all, using the dds object, we take the counts and perform a rlog transformation with the function rlog(). After that, using the function pcaplot() from the R package pcaExplorer we draw the dotplot of the principal component analysis (package pcaExplorer cannot be loaded, so we will use a modification of pcaplot() called pcaplot2()).

rlog_counts <- rlog(dds, blind = FALSE)
pca <- pcaplot2(rlog_counts, intgroup = "condition", ellipse = F, text_labels = F)

Using these samples, it seems that the intra-condition replicates are not extremeley similar between them, since:

  • Replicates from each condition are distributed along all the PC1.
  • Replicates from one condition cluster very close with replicates of other conditions and far from the ones within their condition, specially in the NIT and SFI conditions.

Visualization

Heatmaps

Using the R package ComplexHeatmap we can draw heatmaps comparing the samples or the conditions we wish.

Normalized counts

A good thing we can do is to build a heatmap with the normalized counts of the most differentially expressed genes (100 genes) in the contrast ELI vs NIT. This way, we can look visually at the differences between the different conditions and whether the intra-condition replicates are similar regarding the expression of these genes.

#get 1000 genes more differentially expressed in the first contrasts
genes <- contrast1.res_annot %>% 
  mutate(abs_log2FC = abs(log2FoldChange)) %>% arrange(desc(abs_log2FC)) %>% dplyr::select(Geneid) %>% head(100)

#filter normalized counts
norm_counts_filt <- norm_counts[which(norm_counts$GeneID %in% genes$Geneid),] %>% dplyr::select(c(2:31))

#create heatmap fo normalized counts for the 1000 most differntially expressed genes
h0 <- Heatmap(norm_counts_filt, 
              cluster_rows = F, cluster_columns = F, 
              show_row_names = F, show_column_names = F, 
              column_split = c(rep("NIT",10), rep("SFI",10), rep("ELI",10)),
              name = "Norm. counts", heatmap_width = 5)
h0

As expected, with the most 1000 differentially expressed genes in the contrast ELI vs NIT, the samples in the condition ELI have a high gene expression compared to NIT and SFI. Moreover, we can se that the replicates within each condition are similar between them in terms of normalized gene expression.

MA plots

One of the things we can do to see the DE analysis results is a MA plot, which draws the mean of the normalized counts in the X axis against the log2FC in the Y axis. A useful function to draw MA plots is plotMA() from BiocGenerics package.

contrast1.ma <- plotMA(contrast1.res, main = "Contrast 1: ELI vs NIT", ylim = c(-4,4))

contrast2.ma <- plotMA(contrast2.res, main = "Contrast 2: ELI vs SFI", ylim = c(-4,4))

contrast3.ma <- plotMA(contrast3.res, main = "Contrast 3: SFI vs NIT", ylim = c(-4,4))

Looking at the MA plots, it is easy to say that the SFI and NIT conditions (contrast 3: SFI vs NIT) are very similar in terms of gene expression, since most of the genes in the contrast are aligned in a log2FC value of 0, regardless of the gene expression (mean of the normalized counts). In the other two contrasts, there are more genes with a log2FC of 1 (which mean that the gene expression has increased to the the double or decresed to the half).

Volcano plots

Probably, the most useful way to visualize a DE analysis is through volcano plots, which draw a point for each gene with the log2FC in the X axis and the -log10(adjusted pvalue) in the Y axis. Usually, the color of the points depends on whether the gene is upregulated, downregulated or not differentially expressed.

To draw the volcano plots we will use a custom function named VolcanoPlot2().

contrast1.volcano <- VolcanoPlot2(dataframe = contrast1.res_annot, ylim = c(0,20), main = "Contrast 1: ELI vs NIT", title_size = 13, degsLabel = F)
contrast2.volcano <- VolcanoPlot2(dataframe = contrast2.res_annot, ylim = c(0,20), main = "Contrast 2: ELI vs SFI", title_size = 13, degsLabel = F)
contrast3.volcano <- VolcanoPlot2(dataframe = contrast3.res_annot, ylim = c(0,20), main = "Contrast 3: SFI vs NIT", title_size = 13, degsLabel = F)

ggdraw() +
  draw_plot(contrast1.volcano, x = .25, y = .75, width = .5, height = .5, vjust = .5, hjust = .5) +
  draw_plot(contrast2.volcano, x = .75, y = .75, width = .5, height = .5, vjust = .5, hjust = .5) +
  draw_plot(contrast3.volcano, x = .50, y = .25, width = .5, height = .5, vjust = .5, hjust = .5)

The volcano plots confirm what has been seen with the MA plots: the conditions SFI and NIT (contrast 3) are very similar, since there is no gene called as differentially expressed, even though some have an adjusted p-value lower than 0.05 or an absolute value of log2FC greater than 1.5, but not both at the same time. In the contrast 1 and 2, the number of differentially expressed genes (DEGs) is very similar between them, since the âcontrolâ conditions in these contrasts are NIT and SFI respectively, and we already know that they are similar conditions.

Looking at the effects of the lymphoid infiltration, it increases the gene expression of a large amount of genes, either in the contrast ELI vs NIT or ELI vs SFI, whereas the number of downregulated genes is extremely low in comparison with the activated ones.

Overlaps

To see how many and which differentially expressed genes overlap between different contrast, we can take the lists of gene names (ex. in ensembl id) and, using the custom function overlapDE() we will make the intersection of the DEG lists and plot the Venn diagrams. However, first of all we must separate the upregulated and downregulated genes and, to do it, we will use the custom function subsetDegs().

#subset degs
contrast1_degs <- subsetDegs(contrast1.res_annot)
contrast2_degs <- subsetDegs(contrast2.res_annot)
contrast3_degs <- subsetDegs(contrast3.res_annot)

venn_123_up   <- overlapDE3(contrast1_degs$up, contrast2_degs$up, contrast3_degs$up, 
                            categories = c("1: ELI vs NIT", "2: ELI vs SFI", "3: SFI vs NIT"))
venn_123_down <- overlapDE3(contrast1_degs$down, contrast2_degs$down, contrast3_degs$down, 
                            categories = c("1:ELI vs NIT", "2: ELI vs SFI", "3: SFI vs NIT"))

ggdraw() + 
  draw_plot(venn_123_up, x = .25, width = .5, hjust = .5) +
  draw_plot(venn_123_down, x = .75, width = .5, hjust = .5) +
  draw_plot_label(label = "Contrasts 1 vs 2 vs 3 - Upregulated genes", x = .25, hjust = .5, y = 0.99, size = 16) +
  draw_plot_label(label = "Contrasts 1 vs 2 vs 3 - Downregulated genes", x = .75, hjust = .5, y = 0.99, size = 16)

Venn diagrams show two different things:

  • In the case of the upregulated genes, the contrasts 1 and 2 have a lot of overlapping genes (approximattely 50% for the contrast 1 and more than 90% for the contrast 2), indicating high similarity between them. The contrast 3 has more upregulated genes in common with the contrast 1 than contrast 2, which is interesting, since until now, we have observet higher similarity of contrast 3 with contrast 2 than with contrast 1.

  • When looking at the downregulated genes, the proportion of overlapping genes between contrasts 1 and 2 is much lower than in the case of the upregulated ones, being les than 33% of the genes in the contrast 1 and les than 15% for the genes in the contrast 2. In the case of the contrast 3, it has not any downregulated gene in common with the other two contrasts.

####GO enrichment {goterms}

Another intersting thing to do is an analysis of the GO terms related to the up and downregulated genes (separately). To do so, we will use the R package clusterProfiler.

First, we need to separate the upregulated and downregulated genes from each contrast, take the list of gene IDs and then format them to ENTREZ ID. This process will make us lose some of the genes.

#separate DEGs in up or downregulated genes
contrast1_up   <- contrast1.res_annot %>% filter(DEG == "Upregulated") %>% dplyr::select(Geneid)
contrast1_down <- contrast1.res_annot %>% filter(DEG == "Downregulated") %>% dplyr::select(Geneid)
contrast2_up   <- contrast2.res_annot %>% filter(DEG == "Upregulated") %>% dplyr::select(Geneid)
contrast2_down <- contrast2.res_annot %>% filter(DEG == "Downregulated") %>% dplyr::select(Geneid)
contrast3_up   <- contrast3.res_annot %>% filter(DEG == "Upregulated") %>% dplyr::select(Geneid)
contrast3_down <- contrast3.res_annot %>% filter(DEG == "Downregulated") %>% dplyr::select(Geneid)

#convert gene names from ensembl id to entrez id
contrast1_up   <- bitr(contrast1_up$Geneid, fromType = "ENSEMBL", toType = "ENTREZID", OrgDb = org.Hs.eg.db)
contrast1_down <- bitr(contrast1_down$Geneid, fromType = "ENSEMBL", toType = "ENTREZID", OrgDb = org.Hs.eg.db)
contrast2_up   <- bitr(contrast2_up$Geneid, fromType = "ENSEMBL", toType = "ENTREZID", OrgDb = org.Hs.eg.db)
contrast2_down <- bitr(contrast2_down$Geneid, fromType = "ENSEMBL", toType = "ENTREZID", OrgDb = org.Hs.eg.db)
contrast3_up   <- bitr(contrast3_up$Geneid, fromType = "ENSEMBL", toType = "ENTREZID", OrgDb = org.Hs.eg.db)
contrast3_down <- bitr(contrast3_down$Geneid, fromType = "ENSEMBL", toType = "ENTREZID", OrgDb = org.Hs.eg.db)
go.names <- as.data.frame(c(contrast1_up$ENTREZ, contrast1_down$ENTREZ, 
                            contrast2_up$ENTREZ, contrast2_down$ENTREZ,
                            contrast3_up$ENTREZ, contrast3_down$ENTREZ)) %>%
  set_colnames("ENTREZ")
go.names$condition <- c(rep("ELI vs NIT - Up", length(contrast1_up$ENTREZ)),
                        rep("ELI vs NIT - Down", length(contrast1_down$ENTREZ)),
                        rep("ELI vs SFI - Up", length(contrast2_up$ENTREZ)),
                        rep("ELI vs SFI - Down", length(contrast2_down$ENTREZ)),
                        rep("SFI vs NIT - Up", length(contrast3_up$ENTREZ)),
                        rep("SFI vs NIT - Down", length(contrast3_down$ENTREZ)))

go.dot <- compareCluster(data = go.names,
                         geneClusters = ENTREZ~condition,
                         fun = "enrichGO",
                         OrgDb = org.Hs.eg.db, 
                         keyType = 'ENTREZID', 
                         ont = "BP", 
                         pAdjustMethod = "BH", 
                         pvalueCutoff = 0.1, 
                         qvalueCutoff = 0.15, 
                         readable = TRUE)

#write.xlsx(x = list, file = "results/GO/GOterms_in_DEGs.xlsx")
enrichplot::dotplot(object = go.dot, title = "GO terms enriched in the DE genes", showCategory = 20, color = "p.adjust", font.size = 10, split = F) + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust = 1, vjust = 0.9))

When looking at the upregulated genes, the enriched GO terms are similar in contrasts ELI vs NIT and ELI vs SFI. As seen in the dotplot, these GO terms (biological process) are mainly related to processes of the immune system, such as lymphocyte and leukocyte proliferation or activation.

In the case of downregulated genes, the GO terms are less enriched, specially in the contrast ELI vs NIT, where we had to increase the q-value threshold to see some terms. We also see that downregulated genes of both contrasts have many differences in terms of gene ontologies: while in the ELI vs NIT the enriched GO terms are mainly related to cell fate and development (possibly due to a regression to a less differentiated state of the cells?, i.e.Â cancer, leukemia?), in the contrast of ELI vs SFI, the downregulated genes are more related to signal transduction processes.

In the contrast SFI vs NIT, the enriched GO terms for the upregulated genes are also related to processes of the immune system. However, some GO terms are also related to signal transduction, partially overlapping with those enriched in the downregulated genes of ELI vs SFI
